{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06683c98-3d82-4355-9955-d1cfe3bc054a","content":"Here's what you need to do:\n\n1. **Remove** the `xunit.runner.visualstudio` package reference.\n\n2. **Add** the `xunit.runner.mtp` package instead:\n   ```xml\n   <PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.mtp\" Version=\"*\" />\n   ```\n   *(Use a version compatible with xunit 2.9.3 — check NuGet for the latest.)*\n\n3. **Add** this property to your `.csproj` (or `Directory.Build.props`):\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n   This enables `dotnet test` compatibility with MTP.\n\n4. **Run tests** with:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet test\n   ```\n   Or run the test project directly as an executable (MTP makes your test project a standalone app):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet run --project YourTests.csproj\n   ```\n\n**Key differences to be aware of:**\n- MTP turns your test project into an executable (not a DLL loaded by a host).\n- CLI flags differ slightly (e.g., `--filter` becomes `--treenode-filter`), though `dotnet test` compatibility smooths this over.\n- If you use `runsettings`, review MTP's configuration model — some settings migrate differently.\n\nThat's the core migration. It's generally a straightforward package swap.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ddb94ed3-7a8b-4945-9d92-8fa779972a90","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their xUnit.net project from VSTest (using xunit.runner.visualstudio) to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.","outputTokens":430,"requestId":"4C1E:1414DF:D48478:1080F74:6A0128B7"},"id":"3ef53c65-4dda-4d13-949f-720b88233c64","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:54:25.969Z","parentId":"c1f5e5bf-4570-4ed1-a864-83a043bc3e51"}
